John Edward: Language skills are essential for citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of school excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent examination results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to offer the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and in their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made school program, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desired topics in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to create relationships and establish a trustworthy link with inhabitants of other countries.
If we look at the excellent results of the exams this year, we find that the languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest rating, A.
The data collected from the 74 member schools of the SCIS shows that 72% of students received the highest rating, A in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 British Employment Commission and Skills survey reveals that among the difficulties encountered by employers in recruiting candidates, 17 per cent are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more job offers that require languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
No matter his career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this sustainable competence.
The ability to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a YouGov survey conducted in 2013 with 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them did not master a foreign language enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
That’s why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those in emerging economies, children will benefit from better chances of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on classic contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the perspective of 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to offer a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed for their success, no matter what the future reserves them.
It is obvious that today, in a global business environment, languages remain important for the future of the country, which must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this excellence to Scottish youth.
We need to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
