Harvard: Students Taking Rest Courses
This year, Harvard University has set up a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight the growing machist trend that consists of studying in consuming caffeine all night.
A teacher noticed that most students from the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first in the United States.
After having given a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning, the idea came to him.
At the end, a student approached me and asked, "Why is it told me only in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Spent for the first time this year, this course explains the need for students to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Chief Executive Officer of University Health Services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after found that students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections shows the image of a bedroom containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, basketballs, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical benefits and the importance of integrating a routine before bed.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep lack can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
However, we believe they have the right to know this information - in the same way that you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are,” Professor Czeisler added.
According to him, the culture of pride of “a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and constantly increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having sufficient sleep and good quality should be “the secret weapon” of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain in a mode of inanition, making them hungry constantly.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and forced him to insist on it to be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all graduate students to follow a similar program before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to provide an alarm for both sleep and awakening, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” issued by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleeping disorders.
