Point info on red tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in concentrations of red tide in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County - which fears decreasing concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastlines, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Islands are located about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in less sites than last week.
Red tide was also observed in the county of Pasco.
Moderate concentrations in or off the county of Pinellas were reported last week, low concentrations off the county of Hillsborough, higher concentrations in the county of Manatee, higher concentrations at the bottom of the county of Sarasota or off the county.
Respiratory irritation remains in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in the northwest of Florida last week.
